{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583468"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:15:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:15:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11388"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11388"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.08,0.64,0.02,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4033"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94463"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4033"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77502"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32414"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94463"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with fever, dysuria, and confusion. She has a long-term indwelling urinary catheter and a history of recurrent urinary tract infections with multi-drug resistant organisms. Her medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and chronic kidney disease. Her medications include metformin, perindopril, and amlodipine. She lives independently and works part-time as a librarian.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. She is tender in the suprapubic region. Her catheter is draining cloudy, malodorous urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal a white cell count of 18.2 \u00a0x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0), C-reactive protein 156 mg/L (\u0026lt;5), and urine microscopy shows \u0026gt;100 white cells per high-power field. Previous urine cultures have grown \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E resistant to multiple antibiotics but sensitive to ciprofloxacin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following adverse effects must be considered when prescribing ciprofloxacin for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ototoxicity","Erythematous maculopapular rash","Prolonged QT interval","Tooth discolouration","Deranged liver enzymes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a complicated urinary tract infection and sepsis, likely caused by a multi-drug resistant organism based on her history. Ciprofloxacin, a fluoroquinolone antibiotic, is an appropriate choice given her previous cultures showing \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E sensitive only to this agent. However, when prescribing ciprofloxacin, several adverse effects must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged QT interval\u003C/strong\u003E is a significant adverse effect of ciprofloxacin and other fluoroquinolones. This effect can predispose patients to potentially life-threatening ventricular arrhythmias, particularly Torsades de Pointes. According to the Australian Medicines Handbook, an increase of \u0026gt;20 milliseconds (particularly \u0026gt;60 milliseconds) is considered proarrhythmic. A baseline ECG should be performed prior to commencing treatment to assess the patient\u0027s QT interval, especially in patients with risk factors such as electrolyte abnormalities, cardiac disease, or concomitant QT-prolonging medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOtotoxicity\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily associated with aminoglycoside antibiotics such as gentamicin, amikacin, and tobramycin, rather than fluoroquinolones. Aminoglycosides can cause irreversible damage to the vestibular and cochlear systems, resulting in hearing loss and balance disorders. While fluoroquinolones have been rarely associated with ototoxicity, it is not a primary concern when prescribing ciprofloxacin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythematous maculopapular rash\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with beta-lactam antibiotics, particularly amoxicillin. This adverse effect is especially prevalent in patients with infectious mononucleosis, acute lymphoblastic leukaemia, chronic lymphocytic leukaemia, and HIV infection. While skin reactions can occur with ciprofloxacin, they are not as characteristic as with beta-lactams.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETooth discolouration\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-known adverse effect of tetracycline antibiotics, especially when administered to children under 8 years of age or to pregnant women. This permanent staining occurs due to the binding of tetracyclines to calcium in developing teeth. Ciprofloxacin does not cause tooth discolouration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeranged liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E can occur with many antibiotics, but are particularly associated with flucloxacillin, which can cause cholestatic hepatitis. While ciprofloxacin can occasionally cause transient elevations in liver enzymes, this is not as characteristic or concerning as the QT interval prolongation when initiating therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ciprofloxacin can prolong QT interval, requiring baseline ECG assessment prior to treatment initiation.","Fluoroquinolones should be reserved for resistant infections due to their potential for serious adverse effects.","QT interval prolongation can lead to life-threatening arrhythmias such as Torsades de Pointes."],"references":["Kezerashvili A, Khattak H, Barsky A, Nazari R, Fisher J. Azithromycin as a cause of QT-interval prolongation and torsade de pointes in the absence of other known precipitating factors. Journal of Interventional Cardiac Electrophysiology. 2007;18(3):243-246. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17546486/","Australian Medicines Handbook [online]. 2019. Available at: https://amhonline.amh.net.au/auth."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77502"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11388"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77502"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-24T09:46:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-24T09:46:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4033"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94463"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":n